abstract = {With the growing demands of sustainability in the environment, unmanned aerial systems (UAS) are implemented in almost every monitoring zone, like agriculture, disasters, medical purposes, etc., wherever it is difficult to cover a large area in a limited amount of time in a fast manner. So sustainability was achieved and eased with UAS, but with its new boon, it also suffers from issues with energy sources due to its high mobility. Conventionally, mobile devices create the network in 2D, named ,mobile adhoc network (MANET), but due to fast and high coverage, the new refined system with high flexibility created flying adhoc network (FANET). But the UAS running on battery power suffers from battery drain due to this drastic mobility. Since the UAS completely fly and communicate with routing management, most of the FANET utilises AODV routing, where communication is held through the hello packets, whose intervals are critical to maintain, which were seen being trivially transmitted periodically without indeed. Thus, a new adaptive velocity-based hello interval method was proposed that transmits the hello packet in the peer network according to the speed of the UAS, so the wastage of energy at non-required points could be saved. This would improve the battery power, which would elongate the flight time, as well as their network performance. The scheme is tested over NS3.27, where it results in saving about 4-8% energy and getting benefits in throughput and end-to-end delays as well.},
